@oli-obk I realized the code path is for the value with which a `static` is initialized, not a `const`.
A `const` cannot mention any `static` at all, it's the initializer value of a `static` which can.

Also, the error `constants cannot refer to other statics, insert an intermediate constant instead [E0013]` is very confusing, I'm not sure what it's trying to tell me.

I just checked and it seems that many of these cases just cause the compiler to abort (with SIGILL and no error message), for example ([playpen](https://play.rust-lang.org/?gist=90940f28028322c06b01&version=stable)):

``` rust
fn main() {
    static A: i32 = 0;
    static B: i32 = *&A;
    println!("{:?}", B);
}
```

Though it only happens when the statics are inside a function, so I'm a bit confused as to what's going on.

IMO references to statics should not be dereferenced for any other purpose than to offset them (similar to `&(*(0 as *const Struct)).field as *const _ as usize`, which is no longer allowed).

Is it even possible to deny such uses after 1.0?
cc @alexcrichton @nikomatsakis

@eddyb should this PR be on hold until the static deref issue is fixed since it'd introduce yet another way to do static deref?

EDIT: wait no, it doesn't introduce a new way... it just allows constant evaluation of the index operation

``` rust
const IDXES: [usize; 5] = [5, 6, 2, 8, 9];
const ARR: [i32; IDXES[3]] = [42, 66];
```

cc @rust-lang/lang 

If we're sure that the only new compile errors are where we would previously have had a run-time error and we get a clean crater run, then I'd be happy to merge this. What about the rest of the lang team?

@oli-obk any new thoughts?
